rt 6 Relationships and Communities -- t14 Aesthetics in Friendship and Intimacy -- t15 Morality and Aesthetical Lives: Real Stories of Two Hong Kong Women -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLeading international scholars present analysis and case studies from different cultural settings, East and West, exploring aesthetic interest and experience in our daily lives at home, in workplaces, using everyday things, in our built and natural environments, and in our relationships and communities. A wide range of views and examples of everyday aesthetics are presented from western philosophical paradigms, from Confucian and Daoist aesthetics, and from the Japanese tradition. All indicate universal features of human aesthetic lives together with their cultural variations. Comparative Everyday Aesthetics is a significant contribution to a key trend in international aesthetics for thinking beyond narrow art-centered conceptions of the aesthetic. It generates global discussions about good, aesthetic, everyday living in all its various aspects. It also promotes aesthetic education for personal, social, and environmental development and presents opportunities for global collaborative projects in philosophical aesthetics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAestheticsvCase studies. 0aAesthetics. 0aEast and West. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aAsian Studies. 4aContemporary Society. 4aCultural Studies. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh  aEveryday aesthetics, nature, design, created things, aesthetic experience.1 aBrady, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarvalho, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeng, Peng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l